#### Previous churches

Some buildings have been repurposed, their sacred spaces now serving more secular ends. A partial list of the fallen:

*   [Wallasey Memorial Unitarian Church](/Wallasey_Memorial_Unitarian_Church), on the [Wirral Peninsula](/Wirral_Peninsula), is now cared for by the [Historic Chapels Trust](/Historic_Chapels_Trust).
*   [Upper Brook Street Chapel, Manchester](/Upper_Brook_Street_Chapel,_Manchester), has been converted into [student accommodation](/Student_accommodation), a new kind of sanctuary.
*   [Lewin's Mead Unitarian meeting house](/Lewin%27s_Mead_Unitarian_meeting_house) in Bristol became offices in 1987.
*   New Meeting House, Moor Street, Birmingham, which was rebuilt after the [Priestley Riots](/Priestley_Riots), has been [St Michael's Catholic Church](/St_Michael%27s_Catholic_Church,_Moor_Street) since 1862.
*   [High Pavement Chapel](/High_Pavement_Chapel), Nottingham, is now a pub. Draw your own conclusions.
*   [Platt Chapel](/Platt_Fields_Park), in [Fallowfield](/Fallowfield), Manchester.

Other congregations have moved on, merging with neighbors or simply fading away, leaving only the ghost of a building behind:

*   [Church of the Saviour, Birmingham](/Church_of_the_Saviour,_Birmingham), which helped launch the formidable political career of [Joseph Chamberlain](/Joseph_Chamberlain).
*   [Church of the Messiah, Birmingham](/Church_of_the_Messiah,_Birmingham), an architectural feat built over a canal.
*   [Hope Street Unitarian Chapel](/Hope_Street_Unitarian_Chapel), poignantly situated between Liverpool's Anglican and Catholic Cathedrals, was demolished in 1962.
*   [Octagon Chapel, Liverpool](/Octagon_Chapel,_Liverpool)
*   [Renshaw Street Unitarian Chapel](/Renshaw_Street_Unitarian_Chapel), Liverpool

